  "text": "A horizontally transferred gene would typically experience an abrupt change in its rate matrix when it moves from one species to another. In contrast, all genes in a genome that have not undergone HGT should share approximately the same rate matrix. Thus, we can identify putative HGT genes as those with rate matrices that differ from the rate matrices of other genes in the same species. Different genes within a species can show small deviations in their rate matrices due to differences in transcription and replication [CITATION_1] . For example, deamination proceeds much more rapidly in single-stranded DNA, so genes coded on the leading and lagging strands can experience different rate matrices [CITATION_2] . In addition, differences in the rate matrix inferred from sequence data can occur due to sampling errors. However, these deviations are small compared to the differences between species.",
